title Glowphone requirement refined — a fully-capable repairable phone, not the ascetic sibling
prompt Keaton clarified the Glowphone's only requirements: pocketable, held in the hands, thumb-typed on a touchscreen, with state-of-the-art networking/wireless/storage/battery/chip/camera/sensors/buttons, drop resistance if possible, balanced overall design, and right-to-repair required.
think read this as a decisive correction to the first Glowphone draft, which had leaned toward the Mantrapod's calm-minimal soul. The requirement set is a fully-capable modern smartphone that is also repairable -- the opposite posture from the ascetic e-ink Mantrapod. Named that fork plainly: the two are siblings with opposite postures (subtract capability to return attention vs keep every capability yet refuse the extraction around it).
think grounded it in real 2026 hardware rather than asserting -- searched and found the Fairphone (Gen. 6): Snapdragon 7s Gen 3, 6.31" LTPO OLED 10-120Hz true-black, 50MP OIS Sony Lytia with individually-replaceable camera modules, Wi-Fi 6E, 5G dual-SIM, removable battery, IP55 + Gorilla Glass 7i + MIL-STD-810H drop-tested to 1.5m, iFixit gold-standard modular teardown, 8 Android upgrades to 2033, source published, runs CalyxOS/postmarketOS/e-OS. It most literally satisfies every stated requirement.
think named the one honest tension the requirement surfaces: "state of the art everything" and "fully free firmware" cannot both be maxed, because a flagship modem baseband and camera ISP are the least-free firmware on any phone, proprietary without exception at that tier. Right-to-repair, by contrast, is fully satisfiable now. So the requirement resolves: capability + repairability as hard requirements met, firmware-freedom scoped to "free where the silicon allows, blobs isolated and named" rather than pretended free.
think inverted the draft's Path-A/Path-B lean under the hard repair requirement: Fairphone-class wins (repairable by design), Pixel+GrapheneOS becomes the hardened-but-glued fallback (repairable-with-parts, not by design). The revised strategy: do not fabricate a phone -- reflash a Glow-direction OS onto an already-repairable capable body, heavy AI still on the home forge over Comlink; custom silicon stays a far horizon.
think accreted this as a dated Requirement Refinement section rather than rewriting the draft body, per accrete-never-break and dated_guard -- the first draft stays as the honest record of how the thinking arrived, the refinement corrects in place with its own stamp, exactly as the Glow-supplement doc's own earlier correction did.
think extended the gratitude to thank Fairphone, iFixit, Murena /e/OS, and GSMArena for the dated grounding, nothing copied, per the clean-room discipline.
obs held the "send" convention just seated: Keaton gave a design instruction, not the word "send," so this work is committed to a branch and pushed (saved, reversible) but NOT merged to main -- the merge waits for "send." This is the first turn that tests the new rule, and honoring it plainly matters more than the small convenience of auto-merging.
file external-research/20260715-182500_glowphone-firmware-freedom-two-body-strategy.md -- dated Requirement Refinement section appended; gratitude extended for Fairphone/iFixit/Murena/GSMArena
file external-research/README.md -- index row meaning extended to note the refinement
file session-logs/20260715-191500_glowphone-requirement-refinement.bron -- this log
recommend check-in -- the Glowphone now has an honest, buildable shape (Glow OS reflashed onto a Fairphone-class body) that meets every stated requirement, with firmware-freedom honestly scoped. It is committed and pushed on a branch, awaiting Keaton's "send" to reach main. The next real step is his word to send, or a decision on which base (postmarketOS-maturing vs CalyxOS vs GrapheneOS-fallback) leads.
